Cape Town -  Police have opened an inquest docket into a fatal fire which claimed the lives of a six-month-old baby and two adults. Fire and rescue teams were called to the Marikana Informal Settlement in Philippi on Sunday morning, where they found the remains in the debris. The cause of the fire has yet to be determined after the fire spread from one shack to another, leaving one completely destroyed. Police spokesperson Captain Frederick Van Wyk said their investigation was under way. “Philippi East police are investigating an inquest case,” he said. “According to reports, the SAPS members responded to a fire at M251E, Marikana informal settlement, Philippi East, on February 6, 2022, at 1am. “After the fire was extinguished the bodies of three people, a 40-year-old woman, six-month-old baby boy and a male person were found in the debris. The investigation continues.” The City’s Fire and Rescue spokesperson Jermaine Carelse said the scene had been handed over to the police. “Firefighters were escorted by the SAPS on foot to the incident. The bodies of three persons, two adults and a minor, were discovered amongst the debris of the informal structure. The fire was extinguished at 4.37am and the scene was handed over to SAPS. Last month, Anton Bredell, Western Cape MEC for Local Government, Environmental Affairs and Development Planning received a status report from the province’s Disaster Management Centre on the current fire season in the Western Cape.  Bredell said by the end of January they had already spent more than R10 million on major and small fires in the province. Weekend Argus